defaultThe ‘core tasks’
defaultAs we discussed in our March 2012 submission to the Liaison Committee, our departmentally cross-cutting remit to examine sustainable development makes many of the ‘core tasks’ difficult or inappropriate for us. We do not have a single department whose finances and administration we can scrutinise. Indeed, we have continued to examine the role of more than one department in nearly all of our inquiries. Our 
defaultGreen Economy
default inquiry, for example, covered four departments (Defra, BIS, DECC and Treasury) and 
defaultProtecting the Arctic
default three departments (DECC, Transport and FCO), and in the course of our inquiries since April last year we have covered the work of eight departments. 
defaultAs before, however, we have continued to examine Government policies at an early stage when more readily amenable to change. Our reports on the 
defaultEnergy Intensive Industries Compensation Scheme
default and 
defaultSustainable Development Indicators
default, and ongoing inquiries on 
defaultBiodiversity Offsetting
default and the 
defaultCode for Sustainable Homes
default, all respond to Government consultation exercises. 
defaultInnovative practices
defaultWe hesitate to claim what might be termed ‘innovative practices’. We would highlight the following areas.
defaultWe have endeavoured to take our work away from Westminster when appropriate, particularly when there has been a need to engage with a particular group of stakeholders. We held a seminar at St Martins-in-the-Field in May 2012 to discuss the international sustainability agenda ahead of the UN Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro the following month. Our seminar involved speakers from youth, business, environmental and faith groups as well as Mr Speaker, and took questions from the 500 members of the public present. We launched our ongoing 
defaultGreen Finance
default inquiry at another seminar at the Guildhall in the City of London, and we took formal oral evidence on that same inquiry at the new opened Headquarters of the Green Investment Bank in Edinburgh. We plan to hold a final public event at the City when we publish our report early next year. We have also continued our annual practice of meeting the finalists of the ‘Climate Week’ award scheme, to discuss their initiatives and ideas. 
